SIMPLE: hitch
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hitch
<hw>Hitch</hw> <pr>(h⟦icr⟧ch)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Scot.
<ets>hitch</ets> a motion by a jerk, and <ets>hatch</ets>,
<ets>hotch</ets>, to move by jerks, also Prov. G. <ets>hiksen</ets>, G.
<ets>hinken</ets>, to limp, hobble; or E. <ets>hiccough</ets>; or
possibly akin to E. <ets>hook</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become
entangled or caught; to be linked or yoked; to unite; to
cling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Atoms . . . which at length <qex>hitched</qex> together.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move interruptedly or with halts, jerks, or
steps; -- said of something obstructed or impeded.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Slides into verse, and <qex>hitches</qex> in a rhyme.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To ease themselves . . . by <qex>hitching</qex> into another
place.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To hit the legs together in going, as horses; to
interfere.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj></p>

<p><ent>Hitch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hitch
<hw>Hitch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To <er>hitchhike</er>; -- mostly
used in the phrase to <ex>hitch</ex> a ride; <as>as, he <ex>hitched</ex>
his way home; he <ex>hitched</ex> a ride home</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hitch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hitch
<hw>Hitch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hitched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hitching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To hook; to catch or
fasten as by a hook or a knot; to make fast, unite, or yoke; <as>as, to
<ex>hitch</ex> a horse, or a halter; <ex>hitch</ex> your wagon to a
star</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move with hitches; <as>as, he <ex>hitched</ex>
his chair nearer</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To hitch up</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To fasten
up.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To pull or raise with a jerk; as, a sailor
<xex>hitches up</xex> his trousers.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To attach, as
a horse, to a vehicle; as, <xex>hitch up</xex> the gray mare.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hitch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hitch
<hw>Hitch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A catch; anything that
holds, as a hook; an impediment; an obstacle; an entanglement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of catching, as on a hook, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A stop or sudden halt; a stoppage; an impediment; a
temporary obstruction; an obstacle; <as>as, a <ex>hitch</ex> in one's
progress or utterance; a <ex>hitch</ex> in the
performance.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A sudden movement or pull; a pull up; <as>as, the
sailor gave his trousers a <ex>hitch</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A knot or noose in a rope which
can be readily undone; -- intended for a temporary fastening; <as>as, a
half <ex>hitch</ex>; a clove <ex>hitch</ex>; a timber <ex>hitch</ex>,
etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A small dislocation of a bed or
vein.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hitchel</ent>⟦br⟧
